A team season\n| mode=football\n| year=2017\n| team=Western Kentucky Hilltoppers\n| image=WKU Hilltoppers wordmark.png\n| image_size=200\n| conference= Conference USA\n| division= East Division\n| short_conf= C-USA\n| APRank = \n| CoachRank = \n| record = 6\u20137\n| conf_record = 4\u20134\n| head_coach= [[Mike Sanford Jr.]]\n| hc_year = 1st\n| off_coach= Junior Adams\n| oc_year =1st\n| def_coach =Clayton White\n| dc_year =1st\n| stadium= [[Houchens Industries\u2013L. T. Smith Stadium]]<br>(Capacity: 22,113)\n| bowl = [[2017 Cure Bowl|Cure Bowl]] \n| bowl_result = L 17\u201327 vs. [[2017 Georgia State Panthers football team|Georgia State]]\n}}\n{{2017 Conference USA football standings}}\nThe '''2017 Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football team''' ('''WKU''') represented [[Western Kentucky University]] in the [[2017 NCAA Division I FBS football season]]. The Hilltoppers played their home games at the [[Houchens Industries\u2013L. T. Smith Stadium]] in [[Bowling Green, Kentucky]] as members of the East Division of [[Conference USA]] (C\u2013USA). They were led by first-year head coach [[Mike Sanford Jr.]] The Hilltoppers finished the season 6\u20137, 4\u20134 in C-USA play to finish in a tie for third place in the East Division. They received an invite to the [[2017 Cure Bowl|Cure Bowl]] where they lost to [[2017 Georgia State Panthers football team|Georgia State]].<ref>[https://wkusports.com/documents/2019/7/17/2019_WKU_Football_Media_Guide.pdf WKU Football Media Guide retrieved 31 March 2020.]</ref>\n\n==Previous season==\nThe [[2016 WKU Hilltoppers football team|Hilltoppers]] finished the [[2016 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2016 season]] 11\u20133, 7\u20131 in [[2016 Conference USA football season|C-USA play]] to win a share of the East Division title with [[2016 Old Dominion Monarchs football team|Old Dominion]]. Due to their head-to-head victory over Old Dominion, WKU represented the East Division in the [[2016 Conference USA Football Championship Game|Conference USA Championship Game]] where they defeated [[2016 Louisiana Tech Bulldogs football team|Louisiana Tech]] to be crowned C-USA champions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://collegefootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2016/12/03/wku-outlasts-la-tech-in-record-setting-conference-usa-championship-game/|title=WKU outlasts La Tech in record-setting Conference USA championship game|last=McGuire|first=Kevin|date=2016-12-03|website=CollegeFootballTalk|access-date=2017-09-08}}</ref> They were invited to the [[2016 Boca Raton Bowl|Boca Raton Bowl]] where they defeated [[2016 Memphis Tigers football team|Memphis]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/fl-boca-raton-bowl-football-1221-20161220-story.html|title=Western Kentucky tops Memphis 51-31 in Boca Raton Bowl|last=DeFranks|first=Matthew|work=Sun-Sentinel.com|access-date=2017-09-08|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn December 5, head coach [[Jeff Brohm]] resigned to become the head coach at [[Purdue Boilermakers football|Purdue]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/bigten/2016/12/05/jeff-brohm-western-kentucky-purdue-coaching-vacancy/94993570/|title=Jeff Brohm to leave WKU for Purdue opening|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2017-09-08|language=en}}</ref> He finished at WKU with a record of 30\u201310, two bowl wins, and two C-USA titles. Defensive coordinator [[Nick Holt]] led WKU in the Boca Raton Bowl.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.courier-journal.com/story/sports/college/football/2016/12/16/sanford-waiting-wku-focusing-bowl/95537054/|title=With Sanford waiting, WKU focusing on bowl|work=The Courier-Journal|access-date=2017-09-08|language=en}}</ref> On December 14, the school hired Mike Sanford Jr. as head coach.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bgdailynews.com/sports/wku/wku-hires-mike-sanford-as-head-football-coach/article_36a3fdf0-c214-11e6-a4cf-974a70acf2d4.html|title=WKU hires Mike Sanford as head football coach|last=Stephens|first=Brad|work=Bowling Green Daily News|access-date=2017-09-08|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Preseason ==\nIn a preseason media vote, the Hilltoppers were picked to win the East Division again, receiving 20 of 28 first place votes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/2017/07/19/c-usa-repeat-wku-la-tech-preseason-picks-for-title-rematch/103845860/|title=C-USA repeat? WKU, La Tech preseason picks for title rematch|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2017-09-08|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Schedule and results==\nWestern Kentucky announced its 2017 football schedule on January 26, 2017. The 2017 schedule consists of 6 home and away games in the regular season. The Hilltoppers will host CUSA foes [[Charlotte 49ers football|Charlotte]], [[Florida Atlantic Owls football|Florida Atlantic]], [[Louisiana Tech Bulldogs football|Louisiana Tech]], and [[Middle Tennessee Blue Raiders football|Middle Tennessee]], and will travel to [[FIU Panthers football|FIU]], [[Marshall Thundering Herd football|Marshall]], [[Old Dominion Monarchs football|Old Dominion]], and [[UTEP Miners football|UTEP]].<ref name=\"WKUU17\">{{cite press release|url=http://www.wkusports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/012617aac.html|title=Hilltopper Football Announces 2017 Schedule|publisher=Western Kentucky University Department of Athletics|date=January 26, 2017|accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Hilltoppers will host two of the four non-conference opponents, [[Ball State Cardinals football|Ball State]] from the [[Mid-American Conference]] and [[Eastern Kentucky Colonels football|Eastern Kentucky]] from the [[Ohio Valley Conference]] and travel to [[Illinois Fighting Illini football|Illinois]] of the [[Big Ten Conference]] and [[Vanderbilt Commodores football|Vanderbilt]] from the [[Southeastern Conference]].\n{{-}}\n{{CFB schedule\n| rankyear = 2017\n| poll = [[2017 NCAA Division I FBS football rankings#AP Poll|AP Poll]] released prior to game\n| timezone = Central\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 2\n| time = 6:00 p.m.\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| op